AGI - NATO countries providing weapons to Ukraine should allow the Kiev armed forces to use them also to target military targets in Russia. He said, in an interview with the Economist, Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg. > According to the British weekly, the Alliance leader refers in particular to the United States. "It is time that allies evaluate to eliminate some of the restrictions on the use of weapons that have given to Ukraine," he said in the interview, citing in particular the ongoing battles in the Kharkiv area. "To deny Ukraine the possibility of using these weapons against legitimate military objectives on Russian territory makes it very difficult for them to defend themselves," he explained.&nbsp;
<br The British newspaper explains how for Ukrainians it has long been a source of frustration that, in order to strike targets on the Russian territory, they must depend on the drones produced at home, i.e. tricks with limited utility and effectiveness. Their anger has been weak since May 10, when the Russians have begun a great offensive beyond the border > just 32 km from Charkiv, the second city of Ukraine. The city had already been bombed for several months.&nbsp; Stoltenberg does not expect this action to lead to a turning point for Moscow. "They will continue to push and earn some land, and are willing to pay a very high price for these marginal gains," he said. But warns that Ukraine is in trouble. And he has harsh words for European NATO members: "European allies have promised a million artillery bullets," he said. "We haven't seen anything like this."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In an interview with Afp on 17 May, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-18/guerra-russia-ucraine-interview-afp-zelensky-26434742/">Volodymyr Zelensky</a>, president of Ukraine, asked permission to use donated weapons on Russian objectives. He pointed out that their use would be defensive at a time when Putin's troops are trying to exploit the shortage of labor and ammunition, the latter due to the delay of American support and unmaintained promises of Europe. Western governments, he said, want Ukraine to win so that Russia does not lose." Some Western analysts, writes the Economist, say that America has tried to manage the way Ukraine has fought since the beginning of the war. Several times the Americans denied Ukraine the weapons it had requested urgently, and then cede many months later. The list included the Hears multiple rocket launch system, Abrams tanks, F-16 fighter jets and Atacms, a tactical ballistic missile system.&nbsp; The justification has always been that Washington wanted to avoid an escalation > avoiding an exaggerated reaction by Vladimir Putin, particularly with the use of tactical nuclear weapons. After the French President, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-06/ucraina-putina-nucleare-confine-armi-26283537/">Emmanuel Macron</a>, in May the hypothesis of deploying NATO forces in Ukraine, Putin ordered the conduct of nuclear exercises in Ukraine. However, apart from the game of sabers, Russia's nuclear threats did not lead to anything.
&nbsp;
Stoltenberg recognised the risk of escalation. The task, he said, is "avoid that this war becomes a real war between Russia and NATO in Europe". But he made a distinction between supplying weapons and training and military engagement. "We provide training, weapons and ammunition to Ukraine, but we will not be directly involved in NATO's territory in combat operations above or in Ukraine. So it's different." Stoltenberg traced a similar line on the proposal to station troops in Ukraine if the government requested it, an idea supported by Macron. "This is not the plan... We have no intention of sending NATO ground troops to Ukraine, because our purpose... It is twofold: supporting Ukraine, as we do, but also ensuring that there is no escalation in a large-scale conflict."
&nbsp;
There are now signs that America could move towards the concession to Ukraine of a greater margin of manoeuvre in hitting targets in Russian territory. After visiting Kiev last week, Antony Blinken, Secretary of State, would have exposed in Washington the need to allow Kiev to hit military bases and missile batteries a few kilometers from Russia. These, again explains the Economistl, are used to hit Kharkiv and the troops that defend it. A few days before David Cameron, British Foreign Secretary, declared that Ukraine was free to use British manufacturing Storm Shadow cruise missiles to target Russia. Lloyd Austin, U.S. Secretary of Defense, recently let it be understood that Russian planes flying bombs from Russian airspace could be legitimate targets for American missiles. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
However, Stoltenberg distinguishes between allowing Ukraine to attack targets in Russia with systems donated by the West and any direct NATO engagement in the conflict. His predecessor, Anders Fogh Rasmussen, asked on 14 May that the NATO countries of Eastern Europe can use air defenses on the ground to break down the Russian missiles and drones directed in Ukraine. Stoltenberg rejected this idea: "We will not be part of the conflict," he said.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

